Hi,

I brought this up in IRC yesterday, but I thought it may have seemed to hard to communicate it effectively over just IRC.  I guess this is less of a pull request and somewhat of an issue.  If it is confirmed as an actual issue I'll look into a possible fix as well.  In this pull request, I have added two tests.  The first test (testJodaDateAggregate) would be if I had just used a Joda-like DateTime string without a timezone (e.g. `2015-02-19T12:40:08.626Z`).  This test works perfectly and returns what I expect.  The second test (testDateAggregate) uses a valid ISO8601 format string (e.g. `2015-02-18T14:00:55.958-05:00`) with a timezone associated with it.  Every time this test is run, it will return an error saying that the string parsed is NaN.  For both tests I use the following Javascript function:

``` Javascript
function aggregate(current, startDateString, endDateString) {
    if (startDateString == null || endDateString == null) {
        throw new Error("Date is null.");
    }
    var millisecondsDelta = Date.parse(endDateString) - Date.parse(startDateString);
    var res = millisecondsDelta / (1000 * 60) + current;
    return res;
}
```

Using this function anywhere else seems to work fine with either string.  I admit I didn't try many places, really only Chrome dev console and Node.  What I'm hoping to achieve with this pull request is if Druid would be able to accept such TZ strings in the future or if not, at least have this issue documented somewhere.  Thanks for your time in reading through this! 

Lew
